INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (91,1,'2011-02-21 15:42:51','2011-02-21 15:42:51','SUKRUPA educates and enables more than 400 children from the slums in and around R.T. Nagar, Bangalore, providing a safe, caring, and clean environment for the children to live and learn in while their parents work.\n<h1>Our Programs</h1>\nWe holistically nurture the children and community by providing:\n<ul class=\"lined\">\n	<li>Free Schooling, from pre school through Class 10</li>\n	<li>Youth Training in life skills and distant learning</li>\n	<li>Community and Rural Development</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Residential Program</h3>\nThe SUKRUPA residential program runs a stable, full-time home for up to 10 children. In this loving family environment, children who are orphaned, have single parents or come from families in crisis receive affection, nutrition and guidance. They are provided schooling, education, health care and nutrition, discipline, and mentoring so that they develop as any other child would.\n<div class=\"subarea lhside\" style=\"width: 275px;\">\n<h2>Why It Matters</h2>\nChildren at SUKRUPA come from urban slum communities around Bangalore and are mostly first generation learners.\n\nMany of them come from families whose monthly income is less than Rs. 2,000, which is <strong>less than $50.00</strong>. This leads to a lack of basic needs – like education, health care, and nutrition – and often enters the children into a vicious cycle of child labor and life-long poverty.\n\nDeprivation, poverty, and emotional trauma are a norm, and some children go through severe turmoil and abuse at home and in their communities.\n\n</div>\n<h3>Sukrupa Education Center</h3>\nSUKRUPA Education Centre currently provides free schooling, nutritious food and basic health care to a population of over 400 children who thrive in a clean, safe, friendly and happy environment.\n\n<em>Student Eligibility and Parent Involvement</em>\nSUKRUPA conducts a strict screening process including home visits to determine below of poverty line status and requires a 14 to 16 year commitment of attendance. At the time of admission the parent makes an agreement with SUKRUPA to observe all rules and regulations and to attend child development training sessions every three months. Individual counseling is available per need.\n\n<em>The Curriculum</em>\nThe integrated curriculum at SUKRUPA is distinguished particularly by its emphasis on teaching the arts, social values and right attitude, in addition to academics as essential to a balanced education that produces young adults who are fiscally independent and personally responsible.\n\nSchool activities include:\n<ul class=\"lined\">\n	<li>Academics: Both innovative and traditional teaching methods</li>\n	<li>Languages: English, Kannada, Hindi, German and French</li>\n	<li>Fine Arts</li>\n	<li>Crafts</li>\n	<li>Theater</li>\n	<li>Indian and Western Classical Music and Dance</li>\n	<li>Sports</li>\n	<li>Club Projects in English, Math, Science, Geography, Sports and Horticulture</li>\n	<li>Field Trips</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>SUKRUPA Youth Training Program</h3>\nFor older children and teens who have been child laborers or school drop-outs, the SUKRUPA Youth Training Program is a five year curriculum in personal life skills, social skills, leadership and academics studied through distance learning, provided by the state university.\n\nPractical training in teaching, accounting, sales, computers, conversational English, dance, design, hospitality, housekeeping and crafts, conforms to students’ interests and talents.\n\nYoung women become independent, rather than mothers at the age of 13 or 14. Young men become responsible providers for their families.\n\nIn order to insure continuous participation in this program, each student receives a monthly stipend to help cover family expenses.\n\n<img class=\"lhside\" src=\"http://sukrupa.localhost/content/krupaKids.jpeg\" alt=\"\" />\n<h3>SUKRUPA Outreach Program</h3>\nThis pilot project includes students from the SUKRUPA Youth Training Program. It teaches English to underprivileged urban slum and rural children studying in Kannada Government Schools from Class 1 to Class 7. The children participate in creative activities like art, craft, music, dance, games, and language practice. In 2009, over 400 children participated in this pilot project. We hope to expand it when funding becomes available.\n<h3>SUKRUPA Community Development Program</h3>\nFor women and young adults in the community, particularly the parents and siblings of the children who attend SUKRUPA Education Center, the Community Development Program offers health camps, family counseling, parenting and life skills training as well as vocational training, that constitutes a foundation for dignified employment and self-sufficiency. The ultimate goal of this program is to provide a path out of the slums for relocation to mainstream neighborhoods.\n<h3>SUKRUPA Rural Development Program</h3>\nThis pilot project addresses the challenges of rural poverty as the underlying cause for the formation of urban slums. SUKRUPA has established the project to include four villages in rural Bangalore. The program intends to provide pre-school activities, supplementary education for government school children and vocational training for young adults and older women. Future sources of revenue generation for the villages may include organic farming, dairy farming, and renewable energy.','What We Do','Our mission is to help deprived children and young adults escape a background of poverty, slum life, illiteracy, and ignorance thereby creating opportunities for their integration into mainstream society.','inherit','open','open','','14-autosave','','','2011-02-21 15:42:51','2011-02-21 15:42:51','',14,'http://sukrupa.localhost/uncategorized/14-autosave/',0,'revision','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (92,1,'2011-02-02 09:25:57','2011-02-02 09:25:57','Activities and Programmes.','What We Do','','inherit','open','open','','14-revision','','','2011-02-02 09:25:57','2011-02-02 09:25:57','',14,'http://sukrupa.localhost/uncategorized/14-revision/',0,'revision','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (93,1,'2011-02-07 16:33:42','2011-02-07 16:33:42','SUKRUPA tends to, educates, and enables more than 200 children from the slums in and around R.T. Nagar, Bangalore and creates a safe, caring, and clean environment for the children to live and learn in while their parents work.\r\n\r\n<h3>Where We Work</h3>\r\nChildren at SUKRUPA come from urban slum communities around Bangalore. Many of them come from families whose monthly income is less than Rs. 2,000, which is less than $50.00. This leads to a lack of basic needs &ndash; like education, health care, and nutrition &ndash; and often enters the children into a vicious cycle of child labor and life-long poverty. As a result, the children start working or aimlessly loiter on the streets. Deprivation, poverty, and emotional trauma are a norm, and some children go through severe turmoil and abuse at home and in the community.\r\n\r\n<h3>Our Programs</h3>\r\nWe holistically nurture our children and provide:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Nutritious food each day</li>\r\n	<li>Academic instruction in day school and after school programs</li>\r\n	<li>Health care</li>\r\n	<li>Skills training</li>\r\n	<li>Opportunities to participate in sports and other recreational activities</li>\r\n	<li>Cultural opportunities and awareness</li>\r\n	<li>Training by professionals in dance, music and visual arts</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<strong>Residential Program</strong>\r\nA loving home and care is given for the neediest children, who are orphans, have single parents, or come from battered families. They are provided schooling, education, health care and nutrition, discipline, and mentoring so that they develop as any other child would.\r\n\r\n<strong>Sukrupa School</strong>\r\nSUKRUPA has taken the responsibility of nurturing, educating, and mentoring these children, while taking into account their backgrounds and that their parents: Oftentimes the children are first-generation learners, and their parents often do not have the time, resources, or the awareness to support the growth and development of the children fully &ndash; sadly they may not even understand its intrinsic value.\r\n\r\n<em>Vision</em>\r\nWith the available resources and premises, a high standard curriculum is taught that is both creative and traditional so that children learn with understanding through engagement and personal development. SUKRUPA’s School program provides a quality education that enhances the children’s natural abilities and talents. The program gives them opportunities to realize their dreams and guides them to be independent and responsible people with good values.\r\n \r\n<strong>SUKRUPA Youth Program</strong>\r\n\r\n<em>School Retention</em>\r\nAs the children come from vulnerable backgrounds, we consider it a blessing that the parents have allowed them to continue in school instead of sending them to work as construction or domestic workers. Still, some of the girls do support the family by doing domestic work early in the morning and boys distribute papers or clean cars as the family has huge loans to pay. We are proud that the school dropout rate of children in our development program has dropped from 80% to 5% over the past few years.\r\n\r\n<em>Skills and Leadership Training</em>\r\nAs the community does not value skills training, many people do almost anything that pays money. Most of them are unskilled labors and do not have regular jobs. SUKRUPA has designed a special Life Skills Leadership Program for the 10th, 11th and 12th standard children. The first batch of 18 children participated in this program during the 2008-2009 academic year.\r\n\r\n<em>Building Community</em>\r\nSome of the children are part of a hockey program and the PRAYAAS dance group that requires them to practice on a regular basis. Others pitch in and help at SUKRUPA in teaching, accounting, sales, and designing for which they are provided special training. This assists them with employment at SUKRUPA while they continue their studies through long-distance education programs such as IGNOU till they complete their graduation. During this period they are given a small remuneration that encourages them to stay in school as well as teaching the value of saving.\r\n\r\nThis would mean five years or more for the 10th standard children and three years or more for the 12th standard children. The challenge is how to keep them until such time that they finish their graduation and how to employ them skillfully in various activities at SUKRUPA. If they are not monitored at this stage, the chances of their developing bad habits is at a maximum. As such, parents do not have the time or the know-how, the children themselves are still impressionable, and we feel strongly that it is important to guide these children for three or more years so that they develop deep roots in responsibility and accountability for themselves, for their families, and for the community.\r\n  \r\nWe consider the children at SUKRUPA as our own. We want to provide them the best for their growth in leadership and life skills. Grooming and mentoring them in the right direction is SUKRUPA’s mission and responsibility. Once they finish their graduation they can either continue working at SUKRUPA and take up leadership positions or they are free to work in any other field of their choice. Through this program we at SUKRUPA are confident that we offer a comprehensive program that gives the children a firm foundation that is the basis of a beautiful future.\r\n\r\n<em>Sports & Recreation</em>\r\nChildren are encouraged to participate in sports and various forms of adventure activities. Through different volunteer groups, children are able to play cricket, football, kabbadi, khokho, baseball, to name a few. SUKRUPA conducts competitive annual sports for all the children, and 6 of SUKRUPA boys play field hockey. They are trained at “Dhanraj Ballal Hockey Academy” through our partners at Dream a Dream.\r\n\r\nSUKRUPA also conducts several field trips annually which are both recreational and educational.\r\n\r\n<em>Creative Arts & Crafts</em>\r\nSUKRUPA believes that it is extremely important for the children to be creative for their overall development. Children have the opportunity to learn various arts including classical music, classical dance, free-style dance, drawing, painting, sketching, collage, glass painting, pottery painting, and mural work. Some of the artwork has been made into greeting cards as well. If a child is extraordinary in any art field or has specific talent, special attention is given and s/he is trained under professionals to pursue the specific art. \r\n\r\n<em>Prayaas Performing Group</em>\r\nPRAYAAS is an emerging performing group of SUKRUPA. The group can perform Bharatanatyam, Katak, Contemporary Classical, Freestyle,  Bollywood and Folk Dance. 50% of the revenue generated from the performance is distributed as scholarships among the children who perform, and the other 50% goes into the developmental programs of SUKRUPA.\r\n\r\nThis is a great incentive for the children, considering that most of them are school dropouts who are inducted back into school through our after-school program. Enormous effort and resources go into training them through professional artists in different forms of dance, music, and theatre. The focus and skill is to spot the talents and create opportunities for the children to realize their dreams and grow as independent citizens.\r\n\r\n','What We Do','Our mission is to help underprivileged children escape a background of poverty, slum life, illiteracy and ignorance, replacing these challenges with hope and opportunities available to mainstream children. ','inherit','open','open','','14-revision-2','','','2011-02-07 16:33:42','2011-02-07 16:33:42','',14,'http://sukrupa.localhost/uncategorized/14-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0);
