INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (150,1,'2011-02-07 16:35:47','2011-02-07 16:35:47','SUKRUPA tends to, educates, and enables more than 200 children from the slums in and around R.T. Nagar, Bangalore and creates a safe, caring, and clean environment for the children to live and learn in while their parents work.\r\n\r\n<h2>Our Programs</h2>\r\nWe holistically nurture our children and provide:\r\n<ul class=\"lined\">\r\n	<li>Nutritious food each day</li>\r\n	<li>Academic instruction in day school and after school programs</li>\r\n	<li>Health care</li>\r\n	<li>Skills training</li>\r\n	<li>Opportunities to participate in sports and other recreational activities</li>\r\n	<li>Cultural opportunities and awareness</li>\r\n	<li>Training by professionals in dance, music and visual arts</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<strong>Residential Program</strong>\r\nA loving home and care is given for the neediest children, who are orphans, have single parents, or come from battered families. They are provided schooling, education, health care and nutrition, discipline, and mentoring so that they develop as any other child would.\r\n\r\n<div class=\"subarea lhside\">\r\n<img src=\"http://placehold.it/150x150\" class=\"lhside\" /><h2>Why It Matters</h2>\r\nChildren at SUKRUPA come from urban slum communities around Bangalore. Many of them come from families whose monthly income is less than Rs. 2,000, which is less than $50.00. This leads to a lack of basic needs &ndash; like education, health care, and nutrition &ndash; and often enters the children into a vicious cycle of child labor and life-long poverty. As a result, the children start working or aimlessly loiter on the streets. Deprivation, poverty, and emotional trauma are a norm, and some children go through severe turmoil and abuse at home and in the community.\r\n</div>\r\n<strong>Sukrupa School</strong>\r\nSUKRUPA has taken the responsibility of nurturing, educating, and mentoring these children, while taking into account their backgrounds and that their parents: Oftentimes the children are first-generation learners, and their parents often do not have the time, resources, or the awareness to support the growth and development of the children fully &ndash; sadly they may not even understand its intrinsic value.\r\n\r\n<em>Vision</em>\r\nWith the available resources and premises, a high standard curriculum is taught that is both creative and traditional so that children learn with understanding through engagement and personal development. SUKRUPA’s School program provides a quality education that enhances the children’s natural abilities and talents. The program gives them opportunities to realize their dreams and guides them to be independent and responsible people with good values.\r\n \r\n<strong>SUKRUPA Youth Program</strong>\r\n\r\n<em>School Retention</em>\r\nAs the children come from vulnerable backgrounds, we consider it a blessing that the parents have allowed them to continue in school instead of sending them to work as construction or domestic workers. Still, some of the girls do support the family by doing domestic work early in the morning and boys distribute papers or clean cars as the family has huge loans to pay. We are proud that the school dropout rate of children in our development program has dropped from 80% to 5% over the past few years.\r\n\r\n<em>Skills and Leadership Training</em>\r\nAs the community does not value skills training, many people do almost anything that pays money. Most of them are unskilled labors and do not have regular jobs. SUKRUPA has designed a special Life Skills Leadership Program for the 10th, 11th and 12th standard children. The first batch of 18 children participated in this program during the 2008-2009 academic year.\r\n\r\n<em>Building Community</em>\r\nSome of the children are part of a hockey program and the PRAYAAS dance group that requires them to practice on a regular basis. Others pitch in and help at SUKRUPA in teaching, accounting, sales, and designing for which they are provided special training. This assists them with employment at SUKRUPA while they continue their studies through long-distance education programs such as IGNOU till they complete their graduation. During this period they are given a small remuneration that encourages them to stay in school as well as teaching the value of saving.\r\n\r\nThis would mean five years or more for the 10th standard children and three years or more for the 12th standard children. The challenge is how to keep them until such time that they finish their graduation and how to employ them skillfully in various activities at SUKRUPA. If they are not monitored at this stage, the chances of their developing bad habits is at a maximum. As such, parents do not have the time or the know-how, the children themselves are still impressionable, and we feel strongly that it is important to guide these children for three or more years so that they develop deep roots in responsibility and accountability for themselves, for their families, and for the community.\r\n  \r\nWe consider the children at SUKRUPA as our own. We want to provide them the best for their growth in leadership and life skills. Grooming and mentoring them in the right direction is SUKRUPA’s mission and responsibility. Once they finish their graduation they can either continue working at SUKRUPA and take up leadership positions or they are free to work in any other field of their choice. Through this program we at SUKRUPA are confident that we offer a comprehensive program that gives the children a firm foundation that is the basis of a beautiful future.\r\n\r\n<em>Sports & Recreation</em>\r\nChildren are encouraged to participate in sports and various forms of adventure activities. Through different volunteer groups, children are able to play cricket, football, kabbadi, khokho, baseball, to name a few. SUKRUPA conducts competitive annual sports for all the children, and 6 of SUKRUPA boys play field hockey. T